# Global Instructions

> This is a **template**. Copy to `~/.claude/CLAUDE.md`, delete this quote block,
> and fill in the `<...>` placeholders. Everything below the "Technical Rules"
> divider is generic and can be kept verbatim.
>
> **Design principle:** keep this file short. Skills already inject their own
> descriptions and `SKILL.md` content on demand, so don't duplicate skill
> documentation here. Every line in this file costs tokens on every turn —
> only rules that are *always relevant* belong in the global scope.

---

## User Context

Replace this section with a few sentences about yourself. Claude reads this on
every turn and uses it to tailor explanations. Examples:

```
User is a <role — e.g. backend engineer / PhD student / researcher>.
Working on <domains — e.g. distributed systems / causal inference>.
Prefers <language — e.g. English responses, or Chinese responses>.
```

Keep it short (≤3 sentences). Claude will add more via the `memory/` system over
time.

## General

> Delete this line if you do not want a language preference.
Always respond in `<YOUR_LANGUAGE>` unless the context clearly requires another
language (e.g. writing English papers, code comments in English).

## Explanation Style

> Optional. Keep if you want consistent pedagogical framing.
When explaining technical concepts, start with a concrete example and intuitive
explanation before the abstract formulation.

## Math Formatting

**Always use LaTeX for mathematical expressions.** Use `$...$` for inline math
and `$$...$$` for display math. Never write math as plain text (write
`$E[Y(1) - Y(0)]$`, not `E[Y(1) - Y(0)]`).

