# Technical Rules
# ---------------
# The sections below are generic and safe to keep verbatim. They are the
# "hard rules" that make the workflow skills actually change Claude's behavior.
# Skill-specific protocols (web-access escalation, multi-model review pipeline,
# etc.) intentionally live in each skill's SKILL.md, not here — Claude loads
# them on demand when the skill triggers, instead of paying the token cost on
# every turn.

## Session Continuity (Handoff)

At the start of every conversation, silently check if `HANDOFF.md` exists in
the working directory. If it does, read it before anything else — it is
authoritative context from the previous agent. Do not announce the read.

Pair this with the `handoff` skill: at the end of a significant session, run
`/handoff` (or say "save handoff") to compress the session into `HANDOFF.md`
for the next agent.

## PDF / Image Reading — routing rule

Route PDF/image reading by size and complexity, not as a reflex:

- **Long or complex PDFs** (>20 pages, scanned, heavy math/figure layout) and
  **all images** → hand off to a dedicated extractor (e.g. `pdftotext`,
  `pdfplumber`, or an LLM-based extractor with long context) and use the
  extracted text as context.
- **Short, simple PDFs** (≤20 pages, primarily text, clean digital
  typesetting) → use the built-in `Read` tool directly. No need to spin up
  an extractor.

The 20-page threshold is a heuristic — a math-heavy 15-page appendix is still
extractor territory; a plain 25-page report may not be. When unsure, prefer the
extractor — the cost of a wrong extractor call is small; the cost of blowing
context on a direct `Read` is larger.

## Subagent Dispatch — judgment rules

Parallel subagents (via `Agent` / `Task`) burn real tokens and parent-context;
use them with intent.

**Spawn when**: truly independent fanout (N papers to score, N theorems to
audit, N disjoint codebase searches); multi-persona review (pedantic /
adversarial / generous — lenses, not `reviewer A/B`); multi-model
cross-validation → delegate to the `multi-model-review` skill, don't
hand-roll.

**Don't spawn when**: sequential dependency between agents; one Grep/Glob/Read
suffices; main thread already doing the same work; brief would exceed expected
output; whole task fits in main context.

**Brief standard**: self-contained (subagent sees nothing from parent), explain
WHY not just WHAT, specify output schema and word cap, use absolute paths.
Parallel same-task agents share one output schema and receive lens-specific
briefs.

URL fanout is NOT a subagent case — use `~/.claude/skills/web-access/scripts/fetch-parallel.sh`
(cheaper and purpose-built).

## External-Model CLIs — filesystem isolation

External-model CLIs (GPT / Gemini / Kimi / etc., invoked via their own skills)
cannot read your filesystem — content must be attached explicitly. Each CLI
skill's `SKILL.md` documents its own attachment flags; when in doubt, prefer
`--diff` (for fresh git changes) over stale `-f` files.
